Model training and validation Pipelines¶

We began the semester by using Pipelines to create Pre-Processing workflows that can perform multiple transformations of the inputs. We then focused on the details of fitting different types of models. It's time to revisit Pipelines and therefore merge the programming strategies from the beginning of the semester! In this way you can create detailed model training pipelines that not only pre-process inputs, but also train, tune, and validate predictive models that use features derived from the inputs!

Feature standardization¶

Our features have different scales! If the feature is "big" and the response is single digits, the coefficient multiplying that feature will be small. If the feature is in the single digits and the response is in the single digits, the coefficient can also be in the single digits. Thus, the interpretation of the coefficients is difficult. Which factor or variable matters more cannot be assessed by the magnitude of the coefficient alone.

Although such scale effects do not impact the model performance (usually), we can alter or pre-process the features to make it easier to interpret behavior. A common pre-processing action is standardization which is analogous to calculating the z-score of a feature. We have calculated the standardized features multiple times this semester, but let's just review the calculation one last time.

Standardizing centers a feature by subtracting the empirical (sample) average and then scales by dividing the centered value by the sample standard deviation. For example, if the "raw" feature is $x_{raw}$ the centered variable is:

$$x_{center} = x_{raw} - \mathrm{mean}\left( x_{raw} \right)$$

The standardized variable, $x$, is then:

$$x = \frac{x_{center}}{\mathrm{std}\left(x_{raw}\right)}$$

Models fit using the standardized features have coefficients that must be interpreted in the standardized space.

For example, let's say we have 2 feautres, $x_1$ and $x_2$, and we wish to fit a linear model with linear relationships between them:

$$\mathrm{trend}_{n} = b_0 + b_1 x_{raw,1} + b_2 x_{raw,2}$$

The coefficients (slopes) $b_1$ and $b_2$ tell us how the average trend $\mu$ changes with one unit change of the feature 1 and feature 2, respectively. Again if feature 2 $x_2$ is very large and the response is in the single digits the slope $b_2$ will be small just to have the "units work out".

However, if we first standardize the features,

$$x_1 = \frac{x_{raw,1} - \mathrm{mean}\left(x_{raw,1}\right)}{\mathrm{std}\left(x_{raw,1}\right)} $$$$x_2 = \frac{x_{raw,2} - \mathrm{mean}\left(x_{raw,2}\right)}{\mathrm{std}\left(x_{raw,2}\right)} $$

and then fit our model our linear model with linear additive terms:

$$\mathrm{trend}_{n} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{1} + \beta_2 x_{2}$$

Our coefficients now tell us how the average trend changes with one standardized unit change of the standardized features.

It is much easier to compare "big" vs "small" coefficient values when all inputs are in the standardized space because all inputs will roughly cover the same scale. For example, let's assume our coefficient MLEs in the standardized space give the following model:

$$\mathrm{trend}_{n} = 0.2 + 2.25 \times x_{1} + 0.25 \times x_{2}$$

In the standardized space, we see that if feature 1 increases by 1 standardized unit the average response will increase by 2.25. Feature 2 has a smaller impact, since a 1 standard unit increase results in just a 0.25 unit increase of the average response.

Standardizing the inputs also helps us interpret the intercept as well. The intercept is the value of the average response when the features equal 0. There are many applications where we do not collect values of 0. For example if we wanted to predict the flight distance of a homerun hit in Major League Baseball the air pressure may be a feature we would consider. The pressue is never 0, so our intercept is just a value associated with a hypothetical value of the feature. However, by standardizing the feature, the standardized value of 0 corresponds to the mean! Thus, our intercept tells us the value of the average response when all standardized features are equal to their sample averages!

Response or target standardization¶

We can also standardize the response, just like we standardize features. This is sometimes known as target pre-processing. Doing so can help with interpretation of the coefficients and the intercept. If our original or "raw" response is $y_{raw}$, we can standardize the response using the same procedure described for the feature standardization. The standardized response $y$ is therefore:

$$y = \frac{y_{raw} - \mathrm{mean}\left(y_{raw}\right)}{\mathrm{std}\left(y_{raw}\right)} $$

Let's continue with our example of 2 features and we fit a linear model with linear additive terms. Our model for the average response, $\mu$, with the standardized features "looks" the same as before:

$$\mathrm{trend}_{n} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{1} + \beta_2 x_{2}$$

Except now the average response is the average standardized response. The coefficients now represent the average change of the standardized output due to one standardized unit increase of the feature. The intercept is still the value of the average trend when the standardized features are zero. However, if we do not have categorical inputs, the output might be close to its average when the features are at their averages, and so the intercept could now be close to zero in the standardized output scale.

Standardization and regularization¶

Standardization helps with interpretation, but it is critical to perform when applying regularization. The reason has to do with the formulation of the penalty term as depending on the values of the coefficients. Consider the Lasso or l1 penalty:

$$ \mathrm{Lasso} = \mathrm{strength \ parameter} \times \sum_{d=0}^{D} \left( |\beta_d| \right)$$

The strength parameter term is alpha in sklearn's Lasso() and Ridge() methods, while it is the inverse of C in logistic regression. Let's just drop the parameter, since we know it must be tuned. Thus, the penalty term is proportional to:

$$ \mathrm{Lasso} \propto \sum_{d=0}^{D} \left( |\beta_d| \right)$$

If we use the features in the original or "raw" values, the coefficients might be "small" or "big" just due to the raw natural units of the feature. If we continue to think of our homerun distance example, we might be interested in the ambient (outside) air pressure and the surface roughness of the baseball. If we use Pressure in the SI unit of Pa the outside air pressure is roughly $10^{5}$ Pa which is a "big" number. The surface roughness however is a small number, usually on the order of $10^{-6}$ meters! Our model would therefore have a "big" number and a "small" number to predict something on the order of 300 feet. How could we tell which feature matters or not? The penalty term is going to sum the absolute values of the coefficients together. It does not know or understand there are different units!

For those reasons we should always standardize the features before using Lasso or Ridge regression (or logistic regression with the lasso or ridge penalties). This way we can directly compare "importance" based on the value of the coefficient. The Lasso penalty can appropriately turn-off coefficients that get close to zero.

The summary statistics for each feature are different across the folds! The differences may seem somewhat small in this application, but there are certain types of pre-processing actions where it is critical to correctly apply pre-processing within each fold.

The correct way to apply cross-validation with preprocessing is:

Define resampling scheme.

For each fold perform the followin steps:

  • Apply the preprocessing to the training set (in sklearn terms you must fit then transform)

  • Fit the model using the preprocessed training features

  • Apply the preprocessing to the fold's test set (in sklearn terms you must transform)

  • Predict the hold out test using the preprocessed features

  • Calculate the error at each test point

  • Summarize the error within the fold

Those are a lot of steps! Don't worry though we can use functions to take care of all of that for us! We can define workflows or pipelines which carry out each step correctly.

Create a pipeline¶

Create a "pipeline" of a series of steps to be performed within each cross-validation fold. Another term is the workflow or the work orders.

In [64]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

We will still tune a lasso model, but we will not use the built-in cross-validation method instead we will use the more general GridSearchCV() function.

In [65]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

We must first initialize the objects that we will apply at each step. In our case, that corresponds to a standardization and a lasso model.

In [67]:
standardize_features = StandardScaler()

### Initialize a lasso model object but DO NOT specify alpha
lasso_mod = Lasso(fit_intercept=True, max_iter=10001)

Define the pipeline or the workflow of steps that we execute per fold. The steps must be named and provided the initialized object. The name and object are supplied within a tuple.

In [68]:
lasso_workflow = Pipeline( steps = [('std_scale', standardize_features), 
                                    ('lasso', lasso_mod)] )
In [69]:
lasso_workflow.steps
Out[69]:
[('std_scale', StandardScaler()), ('lasso', Lasso(max_iter=10001))]

We must define the grid of candidate tuning parameter values for GridSearchCV() to use. The grid must be defined within a dictionary where the keys represet the parameter names. The keys associated with a pipeline must be named as:

<step name>__<model parameter name>

The step name and model parameter name are separated by a "dunder" or double-underscore.

In [70]:
lasso_grid = {'lasso__alpha': lasso_cv.alphas_}

Initialize the GridSearchV() object providing the pipeline, the tuning grid, the cross-validation object, and how we will score the model. The options for scoring:

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/model_evaluation.html#scoring-parameter

We saw how R-squared behaves oddly for this example, so let's continue to use MSE as the performance metric of interest. The scoring argument is set to neg_mean_squared_error so that way sklearn understands to maximize the NEGATIVE RMSE (which is equivalent to MINIMIZING the RMSE).

In [71]:
lasso_search = GridSearchCV(lasso_workflow, param_grid=lasso_grid, cv=kf05, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

Execute the cross-validation, use the original un-standardized input-features.

In [72]:
lasso_search_results = lasso_search.fit(X_sk, y_sk.ravel())

Polynomial features¶

sklearn includes numerous preprocessing operations we could perform within a pipeline. In fact, we do not need to pre-create the polynomial features for this example! There is a sklearn function which generates the features for us!

The PolynomialFeatures() is imported below.

In [106]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures

We will not use dmatrices() to create the input feature array because of PolynomialFeatures(). However, we need to perform a few steps first before we can use PolynomialFeatures(). Let's first isolate the input and output variables.

In [107]:
xinputs = demo_df.loc[:, ['x']].copy()
youtput = demo_df.loc[:, ['y']].copy()

Next, let's convert them into NumPy arrays.

In [108]:
X_train = xinputs.to_numpy()
y_train = youtput.y.to_numpy().ravel()

All polynomial features can be created with a single function call as shown below. The polynomial degree is specified by the degree argument. The include_bias argument specifies if the "intercept column of 1s" should be include or not. By default it is and so include_bias is set to False to only return the features. The result below is converted to a DataFrame to make it easy to tell display the resulting feature names and values.

We can therefore modify our pipeline to create the polynomial features for us! We therefore do not have to necessarily precreate the features! Furthermore we can include additional preprocesssing steps like standardization!!! The pipeline below first standardizes the input, generates the polynomials, then standardizes the polynomial features, before using the Lasso model.

In [111]:
lasso_poly_wflow = Pipeline(steps=[('std_input', StandardScaler()),
                                   ('make_poly', PolynomialFeatures(degree=8, include_bias=False)),
                                   ('std_poly', StandardScaler()),
                                   ('lasso', Lasso(fit_intercept=True, max_iter=25001))])

Let's use the same alpha tuning parameter values within our grid search to tune the Lasso model.

In [112]:
lasso_poly_search = GridSearchCV(lasso_poly_wflow, param_grid=lasso_grid, cv=kf05, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

The grid search is applied but notice we are using the original training inputs! We are not using the pre-calculated polynomials in this case!

In [113]:
lasso_poly_search_results = lasso_poly_search.fit( X_train, y_train )

The benefit of this approach is that we can manage input values rather than pre creating most of the features! This also greatly simplifies making predictions! We can make the new input data using the original input values! The Pipeline generates all features and preprocesses them for us!

Summary¶

This report shows how Pipeline and GridSearchCV can greatly streamline the model training, tuning, and validation process. Preprocessing is executed by the model object rather than requiring us to manually create all features.
